<div type="definition">
<p>DELIBERATE DILIGENT TRY:attempt to SUCCEED in an ACTION.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The most general word for physical (and sometimes also mental) effort is perhaps miǎn 勉.</p>
<p>2. Láo 勞 (ant. yì 逸 "failure to put in an effort, relaxed attitude") emphasises the strenuousness and the tiresome nature of effort, and is the most widely used word.</p>
<p>3. Lì 力 emphasises the strength needed to make a effort.</p>
<p>4. Wù 務 emphasises the dutifulness of effort. NB: the meaning "strive to" is separate. See STRIVE FOR.</p>
<p>5. Qín 勤 refers to an honest and strenuous effort.</p>
<p>6. Yòng xīn 用心 focusses on concentration and the consciousness of an effort.</p>
<p>7. The common word jìn 盡 is sometimes used to refer to an all-out effort to do something.</p>
        </div>
